<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF209-821-035  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 821 035.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Design  Feb 6 1989 v28 n3 p42(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Futurebus establishes foothold as model for next-generation bus.andO;(the merger of VME International Trade Association's NextGeneration Architecture Working Group and the IEEE Futurebus andRugged Bus committees)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Andrews, Warren.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The merger of VME International Trade Association's NextGeneration Architecture Working Group (NGAWG) and IEEE Futurebusand Rugged Bus committees means the next-generation bus will bebased on the IEEE Futurebus specification 896.1-1987.andP;  Thecombined group must work hard to have a draft specification readyby mid-1989 as scheduled, however; the proposed bus must bescalable in bus width and transfer speed, and it must support suchfeatures as memory caching coherency, sophisticated arbitration,fast pipelined transfers, self-diagnostics, board ID and hotinsertion.andP;  The new bus must also share a commonality of softwarewith VMEbus at the operating system level and below, according tothe NGAWG; a subcommittee has been formed by the NGAWG to developa bridge specification from the current VMEbus to the new bus.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BusesFuturebus+Trade and Professional AssociationsCommitteeStandardizationSpecificationsProduct DevelopmentVMEbusInstitute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   A multiplexed parallel protocol. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>